EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low moved over the Southern and Central Plains region during the day on Sunday. Adequate moistening and sunshine allowed for modest instability to build within a narrow corridor across central Oklahoma. Isolated thunderstorms developed along a pacific front/dryline feature during the mid afternoon hours. These storms occasionally exhibited supercell characteristics, producing large hail and funnel clouds. One very brief tornado occurred over northeastern Oklahoma county. No damage or injuries occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: From KWTV helicopter video. The tornado lasted less than a minute and no damage was observed or reported.
